# UI Component Tests

**Use When**: Testing rendered React components that depend on Thunder module lifecycle, IDB-backed data, dispatchers, or Thunderstorm UI primitives. The component under test must remain exactly as it is used in the app.

**Builds on**: [Playwright Browser Tests](./playwright-tests.mdc) — same infrastructure (Playwright + Vite + `index.html` + `*.test.playwright.ts`). This rule only documents what differs. For shared infrastructure (test HTML page, running tests, debugging, common issues), see that rule.

## Core Principles

The component is the real component. The modules are the real modules. IDB is real. The only difference from production is where the data comes from — `onEntriesUpdated` instead of `smartSync`.

### One component, one page, one point of failure

Each test renders **exactly one component with one set of props** on its own page. Never render multiple components — or even multiple variants of the same component — on a shared page.

Why: components on a shared page are coupled. An overlay steals clicks from an unrelated button test. A crash in one component unmounts the React tree and cascades false failures to every other test. You debug the wrong thing.

One test entry = one `index.html` + one `test-entry.tsx` = one component instance. If you need to test 3 prop variants, that's 3 entries and 3 pages.

### Thunder initialization

Components extending `ComponentSync` / `BaseComponent` call `Thunder.getInstance()` on mount and unmount for UI listener registration. If no `Thunder` instance exists, the entire React tree crashes.

Every test entry that renders a Thunder component must create a `Thunder` instance before rendering — even for "pure-props" components:

```tsx
import {Thunder} from '@nu-art/thunder-core';
new Thunder({configUrl: '/test-config.json'});
```

This goes at the top of the file, before any component imports that might trigger module-level side effects.

## What Differs from Playwright Browser Tests

| Concern | [Playwright Browser Tests](./playwright-tests.mdc) | UI Component Tests (this rule) |
|---------|------------------------------------------------------|--------------------------------|
| Tests what | JS APIs (IDB, DB-API internals) | Rendered React components |
| Assertions | `page.evaluate()` return values | DOM locators, screenshots |
| Test entry | Exposes classes/utilities on `window` | Boots modules, seeds data, renders JSX |
| Uses modules | Creates fresh instances inside `evaluate` | Uses real singleton modules via `ModuleManager.build()` |
| Vite config | Shared thunderstorm config (`_thunderstorm/vite.config.ts`) | Package-local `vite.test.config.ts` (monorepo resolution) |
| File extension | `test-entry.ts` | `test-entry.tsx` (JSX) |

## Package Structure

Identical to [Playwright Browser Tests](./playwright-tests.mdc) with two differences: per-component isolation and a package-local Vite config.

Each component gets its own folder under `test/` with an isolated entry point:

```
{PackageRoot}/
├── src/
│   ├── main/
│   └── test/
│       ├── {component-a}/
│       │   ├── index.html                     # Loads only this component's entry
│       │   ├── test-entry.tsx                 # Boots modules, seeds data, renders ONE component
│       │   └── {component-a}.test.playwright.ts
│       ├── {component-b}/
│       │   ├── index.html
│       │   ├── test-entry.tsx
│       │   └── {component-b}.test.playwright.ts
│       └── _helpers/                          # Shared constants, utilities (no rendering)
│           └── test-constants.ts
├── playwright.config.ts                       # Points at vite.test.config.ts (not the shared config)
└── vite.test.config.ts                        # Package-local Vite config for monorepo resolution
```

Each `index.html` loads only its sibling `test-entry.tsx`. Each test file navigates to its own `index.html`. No shared rendering page.

## Test Entry (`test-entry.tsx`)

Each test entry renders **one component with one set of props**. It does three things in order: initialize Thunder, boot modules (if needed), render the component.

**Pure-props component** (no module dependencies):

```tsx
import {Thunder} from '@nu-art/thunder-core';
new Thunder({configUrl: '/test-config.json'});

import * as React from 'react';
import {createRoot} from 'react-dom/client';
import {MyComponent} from '../../main/ui/MyComponent.js';

const root = createRoot(document.getElementById('test-root')!);
root.render(<MyComponent title={'Test Title'} count={42} />);

window.TestReady = true;
```

**Component with module dependencies:**

```tsx
import {Thunder} from '@nu-art/thunder-core';
new Thunder({configUrl: '/test-config.json'});

import * as React from 'react';
import {createRoot} from 'react-dom/client';
import {ModuleFE_Channel} from '../../main/modules/ModuleFE_Channel.js';
import {ChannelList} from '../../main/ui/ChannelList.js';

const init = async () => {
	await new Thunder({configUrl: '/test-config.json'})
		.addModulePack([ModuleFE_Channel])
		.build();

	await ModuleFE_Channel.onEntriesUpdated([
		{_id: 'ch-1', title: 'Test Channel', __created: 1, __updated: 1, _v: '1.0.0'}
	]);

	const root = createRoot(document.getElementById('test-root')!);
	root.render(<ChannelList />);
	window.TestReady = true;
};

init();
```

## Vite Config (`vite.test.config.ts`)

Product packages in a pnpm monorepo need a package-local Vite config. The shared thunderstorm config (`_thunderstorm/vite.config.ts`) works for infrastructure packages but product packages pull in deeper dependency trees through barrel exports.

Key settings:
- **`preserveSymlinks: false`** — lets Vite follow pnpm symlinks to the real package location, where each package's own dependencies are properly linked.
- **`vite-plugin-svgr`** — packages that transitively import SVG icons (e.g. via `@nu-art/ts-styles`) need `vite-plugin-svgr` with `include: '**/*.svg'`, `svgrOptions: { exportType: 'named', namedExport: 'ReactComponent' }`. Add it as a devDependency.
- **React deduplication** — packages using React components need `resolve.dedupe: ['react', 'react-dom', 'scheduler']` and `optimizeDeps.include` for React to prevent duplicate React instances in pnpm's strict layout.
- **`server.fs.allow`** — must include the monorepo root so Vite can serve files from any linked package.

Reference implementation: `market/youtube/sampler/frontend/vite.test.config.ts`.

The `playwright.config.ts` is the same as the [Playwright rule](./playwright-tests.mdc) except the `webServer.command` points at `vite.test.config.ts` instead of the shared config.

## Data Seeding Pattern

The core pattern for module-dependent components:

1. **Boot**: `new Thunder({configUrl: '/test-config.json'}).addModulePack([...modules]).build()`
2. **Seed**: `ModuleFE_X.onEntriesUpdated([...fixtures])` — writes to IDB and populates MemCache
3. **Render**: `root.render(<Component />)` — component reads from cache via normal dispatcher flow

The component does not know it's in a test. It reads from `cache.all()` / `cache.filter()` the same way it would in the real app. The dispatcher fires the same way. IDB stores are real.

### Login / Auth

For most component tests, login is irrelevant — the component renders from cached data regardless of auth state. When auth is needed (rare), create a mock JWT with the required scopes and inject it before rendering.

## Writing Tests

Each test file navigates to its own component's `index.html`. Use Playwright locators to assert on what the component renders — not `page.evaluate()` return values:

```typescript
import {expect, test} from '@playwright/test';

const testPagePath = '/src/test/status-badge/index.html';

test.describe('StatusBadge – active', () => {
	test.beforeEach(async ({page}) => {
		await page.goto(testPagePath);
		await page.waitForFunction(() => (window as any).TestReady === true);
	});

	test('shows correct badge and count', async ({page}) => {
		await expect(page.locator('.badge')).toHaveText('active');
		await expect(page.locator('.count')).toContainText('100');
	});
});
```

### Screenshot Assertions

For visual regression, use snapshot matching:

```typescript
test('card renders correctly', async ({page}) => {
	await page.goto('/src/test/card/index.html');
	await page.waitForFunction(() => (window as any).TestReady === true);
	const screenshot = await page.locator('[data-testid="card"]').screenshot();
	expect(screenshot).toMatchSnapshot('card.png');
});
```
